What AWS Lambda actually is?

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OJrxbr9ebDE

s3 trigger with lamda when file upload

It’s a serverless compute service:

You upload your code (called a function)
AWS runs it only when triggered
You don’t manage servers, scaling, or infrastructure

Lambda Timeout Limits

Minimum timeout : 1 second
Maximum timeout : 15 minutes (900 seconds)
Default timeout : 3 seconds

Lambda Other Limits

Timeout        : 15 minutes max
Memory         : 128 MB to 10 GB
Storage (/tmp) : 512 MB to 10 GB
Package size   : 50 MB (zip) / 250 MB (unzipped)
Concurrency    : 1000 per region (default)
Payload size   : 6 MB sync / 256 KB async

Simple Answer

Lambda = short tasks only ✅
  max 15 minutes
  no exceptions

Need longer?
  ✅ ECS/Fargate    → no limit
  ✅ EC2            → no limit
  ✅ Step Functions → chain lambdas
  ✅ AWS Batch      → batch jobs

Step Functions — Solve Lambda Limit

Long task that needs 2 hours:

Step Functions:
  Lambda 1 (15 min) → process chunk 1
        ↓
  Lambda 2 (15 min) → process chunk 2
        ↓
  Lambda 3 (15 min) → process chunk 3
        ↓
  ...continues until done ✅

Each Lambda runs 15 mins max
Step Functions orchestrates them
Total workflow can run 1 year ✅

⚙️ How it works
You write a function (Python, Node.js, Java, etc.)
You set a trigger (event)
Lambda runs your code automatically

Common triggers:
File upload to Amazon S3
HTTP request via Amazon API Gateway
Database updates (e.g., DynamoDB)
Scheduled jobs (cron)


